h3. Summary
The Jira Control Chart doesn't handle recursive transitions (from a given to status to itself) correctly. It will only count the time spent in the first "cycle" on that status.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a Scrum Project;
# Create a Sprint;
# Create an issue and put in in the Sprint then start the Sprint;
# Transition the issue from "To Do" to "In Progress";
# From "In Progress", wait a couple of minutes and then execute the transition to "In Progress";
# Wait another couple of minutes and execute the transition to "Done";
# Go to the board > Reports > Select Control Chart > Select All Columns 
# Click on the issue on the chart and it will only show the cycle time for the first cycle in the "In Progress" status. For example:
{quote}
* To Do = 3m
* In Progress = 2m
* Cycle Time = 5m
!loop1.png|thumbnail!
{quote}

Using [Jira Suite Utilities|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/plugins/com.googlecode.jira-suite-utilities], you can see the time for the second cycle in the "Transitions" panel.

!loop2.png|thumbnail!

h3. Expected Results
The report should sum up "Cycle Time" for the two cycles in that status, or for as many cycles that might happen.

h3. Actual Results
Cycle Time is only calculated for the first cycle in the status.
 
h3. Notes
This is actually an expected behavior according to the [Control Chart documentation|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirasoftwareserver0713/control-chart-965542669.html]:
{quote}
[...]
*Tip 3: Exclude current work*
The Control Chart shows data for issues that have been in a selected column but are no longer in a selected column. This gives the cycle time (total elapsed time) for the issues. However, by default this will include issues which are still moving across the board.
[...]
{quote}

h3.Workaround
Do not transition issues to the same status.

See screenshot for details. There is some incorrect padding and margin being set on some buttons on agile boards.

Taking the 10px padding-left off this:

{{#ghx-view-modes, #ghx-view-tools, #ghx-view-presentation, .ghx-view-section}}

And then adding 10px right-margin on this:

{{.aui-button.ghx-dropdown-trigger}}

Seems to fix at least the first problem.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *JIRA Software Server*. Using *JIRA Software Cloud*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSWCLOUD-12092].
  {panel}

When I click on a quickFilter to edit it, it goes blank. But this only occurs in Chrome. It is working in FireFox. Maybe it is just me. Maybe I have a chrome extension that is causing issues.

If it isn't just me, maybe it is the latest version of Chrome that got rolled out. I did see that there was an update this week.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Software Server*. Using *JIRA Software Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSWCLOUD-12083].
  {panel}

At the moment, to facilitate adoption of a feature we implemented to improve manipulation of sprints throughout JIRA's UI, *the Sprint field will be added to all Create/View/Edit screens (the screens used by the project) each time a new project is created and enabled for Agile*. This is actually an improvement based on the highly voted ticket, as mentioned in [GHS-10767|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/GHS-10767].

However, in the case where the screens are shared accross multiple projects, this automation (sprint will gets automatically re-added into screens) will affect other projects, as they share the same screens. It would be better to have the *options* for the Sprint field to *NOT be automatically re-added* whenever a new project is created and enabled for Agile.
